What I say to my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad, and my foreign friends always ask, with varying degrees of confusion: but what is happening in your country?
Here is what I tell them.
First, be careful not to misinterpret the 2016 elections.
Unlike some comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elites.
Donald Trump tapped into the vein of a tradition associated with leaders such as Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the nineteenth century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the twentieth century.
Yet Trump came within three million votes of winning the popular vote.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If hundreds of thousands of votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
This said, Trump's victory raises the real issue of the rise in social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the significant difference between California and the Appalachians.
The research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among non-college-educated white individuals are worse than those of African Americans, who historically occupied the lower end of inequalities.
In 1999, mortality rates among whites without higher education were around 30 percent lower than those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30 percent higher.
In addition, employment in industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for white working-class individuals, has significantly declined over the last generation, accounting for only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were swayed by Trump's promises to make things change and bring jobs back to industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may well make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that one should not underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and his scandalous disdain for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is monopolizing the viewers' attention, and that the best way to do so is to make extreme statements without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract from his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his self-centered permanent campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that deters some allies whom he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote moves toward the political center in order to attract more support.
That is what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
In contrast, Trump claims that he won the popular vote and pleases his base voters by acting as if that were truly the case.
Although Trump made solid centrist appointments to the Department of Defense, State, and Homeland Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services sit at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists—and he intends to please both camps at once.
Fourthly, one should not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling and ask me if Trump is a dangerous narcissist as bad as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite its many problems, is not the Italy of 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure that the government be harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that makes the exercise of these powers difficult.
A joke about this matter says that the founders created a political system such that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us—impossible for him or for anyone.
Inefficiency was put to the service of freedom.
Trump's presidency is still in its early stages, and we cannot be certain what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
So far, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have upheld this system of checks and balances within the administration, as Madison wished.
And the permanent executive service officials still carry weight.
Finally, my friends are wondering what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I'm less worried about the rise of China than about that of Trump.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about the freeriders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing significant global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems with the international order under U.S. leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can be certain that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first candidate from a major party in 70 years to question the U.S. alliance system.
Since taking office in January, statements by Trump and his members suggest he is likely to persist.
The power to constrain and the power to persuade the United States, after all, largely comes from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
The director of Trump's budget speaks of a budget of constraint, with budget cuts made to the State Department and the United Nations system.
Other members of the government argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with bilateral "fair and balanced" arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to reassure them on these issues.
But I cannot.
